10-Day Update
Narrative:
This is a follow up to the e-mail submitted on January 6, 2024, during the portal maintenance period, and to the supplemental disclosure submitted on January 8, 2024, through the portal. This report supplements and clarifies the previous submissions. 
The incident occurred about 09:50 PST on Jan [XXX], 2024 near the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX], Las Vegas, NV. There were no injuries reported to Aptiv as a result of the crash involving the subject vehicle.
The subject vehicle with Level 2 ADAS engaged was southbound on [XXX] approaching  [XXX].  The subject vehicle was traveling about 30 MPH in the right lane.  An e-scooter was southbound ahead of the subject vehicle in the right turn lane of [XXX] (in the roadway).  The e-scooter then drove into the pedestrian cross-walk from the designated right turning lane, crossed [XXX] and attempted to enter the north/south sidewalk from the roadway.  After entering the sidewalk, the rider of the e-scooter lost control and the rider and e-scooter re-entered the right lane of [XXX].  The rider fell into the road near the curb where he remained, but the e-scooter slid out from under the rider and continued to slide across the roadway until its front wheel reached the middle of the right lane.  The subject vehicle was not involved with nor did it contribute to the rider of the e-scooter losing control or with either the e-scooter or rider re-entering the roadway.
The subject vehicle driver was monitoring the e-scooter and had prepared to react when he noticed the e-scooter attempting to enter the sidewalk.  The subject vehicle driver manually applied the brakes when the e-scooter lost control and entered the roadway from the sidewalk.  The driver's application of the brakes automatically disengaged the Level 2 ADAS system.  The subject vehicle driver also moved left in lane, but was limited by an adjacent vehicle.  The subject vehicle made contact and damaged the front wheel of the e-scooter.  The subject vehicle did not contact the e-scooter rider or any other vehicles at any point.

10-Day Update
Narrative:
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted.
On July [XXX], 2022 at 3:26 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] when it detected a siren from a nearby emergency vehicle. As the Waymo AV slowed, a passenger vehicle made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the drivers seating position). Both vehicles sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate to the report submitted by Waymo LLC WaymoLLC-[XXX].

Report Type: 10-Day Update
Narrative:
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted.
On July [XXX], 2022 at 12:57 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) was traveling eastbound on [XXX] in autonomous mode when a pedestrian entered the roadway from the center median. The test driver then disengaged autonomous mode and braked to a stop as the pedestrian began to run toward the Waymo AV. The pedestrian stood in front of the vehicle, then jumped onto the hood of the Waymo AV and used their body to break the Waymo AVs windshield. The pedestrian was apprehended soon after by nearby police. The Waymo AV test driver was not physically injured but was taken to a nearby hospital out of an abundance of caution. The Waymo AV sustained major damage to its windshield.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event to ensure official notification to the agency of a notable event. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate to WaymoLLC-[XXX].

1-Day
Narrative:
On July [XXX], 2022 at 12:57 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) was traveling eastbound on [XXX]  in autonomous mode when a pedestrian entered the roadway from the center median. The test driver then disengaged autonomous mode and braked to a stop as the pedestrian began to run toward the Waymo AV. The pedestrian stood in front of the vehicle, then jumped onto the hood of the Waymo AV and used their body to break the Waymo AVs windshield. The pedestrian was apprehended soon after by nearby police. The Waymo AV test driver was not physically injured but was taken to a nearby hospital out of an abundance of caution. The Waymo AV sustained major damage to its windshield.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event to ensure official notification to the agency of a notable event. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate to WaymoLLC-[XXX].

Narrative: According to the police report, at the time of the incident a 2016MY Chevrolet Impala was stationary northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane facing northwest.  The 2021MY Kia K5 was traveling northbound on [XXX], in the inside lane approaching the Chevrolet Impala. A 2008MY Honda Civic was traveling northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane behind the Kia K5.  Subsequently, the Kia K5's front struck the Chevrolet Impala's drivers side rear door and rear quarter panel.  After impact, the Impala traveled in a northwesterly, counterclockwise direction into a concrete barrier wall and bounced off the barrier wall and redirected to a northeasterly counterclockwise direction across the northbound lanes when the Honda Civic's front collided into the Chevrolet Impala's and left rear door.  The Chevrolet Impala came to rest facing north, blocking the inside lane. After impact, the Kia K5 traveled in a northeasterly direction across the northbound lanes and came to a final rest on the outside grass shoulder facing west.  The Honda Civic came to final rest blocking the outside lane adjacent to the Chevrolet Impala.  The subject Kia K5 is equipped with Highway Driving Assist (HDA).  HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance and speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway and helps keep the vehicle between lanes while driving.  HDA may not be able to recognize all traffic situations and may not detect possible collisions due to limitations of the system.  Obstacles such as vehicles, motorcycles, bicycles, pedestrians, unspecified objects and structures that may collide with the vehicle may not be detected. The owner (father of the driver) of the Kia K5 contacted Kia's Consumer Affairs Department on August [XXX], 2021 indicating that his son was involved in an accident.  The father was not a passenger or witness to the accident.  The father reported that HDA was engaged at the time of the incident and stated that his son "had the autopilot on and there was a vehicle in the middle of the road and it [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] did not notify his son."  According to the father, the police removed the "black box" from the vehicle.  The claims made by the driver's father have not yet been confirmed, and we note that the subject vehicle has no "autopilot" nor does Kia America advertise any ADAS feature as "autopilot."  Kia has no further information at this time.**9/[XXX]/2021 - No incremental information available as of 9/[XXX]/2021 2:26PM (PDT)

Narrative:
This single-vehicle crash involved a 2018 model year Cadillac CT6 vehicle.  GM's current understanding of the crash is based on OnStar telematics data and the driver's statements after the crash to an OnStar representative.   Before the crash, the vehicle was proceeding straight on a freeway road with Super Cruise engaged.  The driver reported to OnStar that the cause of the crash was his inadvertent contact with the steering wheel that occurred when he bent down to pick something up off the floor of the vehicle.  This is consistent with telematics data, which indicates that the driver provided a manual override input into the steering wheel approximately four seconds before the crash.  This steering wheel input simultaneously disengaged Super Cruise and caused the sequence of events that led to the vehicle crashing into a fixed on-road barrier.  Super Cruise was not active at the time of the crash.  After the Crash, OnStar Emergency contacted the driver and found out the driver was alert and responsive, and requested emergency assistance.  GM believes, but has not confirmed, that the vehicle was towed from the scene.  Telematics data indicates that the driver was not belted at the time of the crash.   GM does not know whether the driver or any vehicle passengers were injured during the crash.
Since the time of submission, there is no new information at this time to update.

1-Day
Narrative: This single-vehicle crash involved a 2018 model year Cadillac CT6 vehicle.  GM's current understanding of the crash is based on OnStar telematics data and the driver's statements after the crash to an OnStar representative.   Before the crash, the vehicle was proceeding straight on a freeway road with Super Cruise engaged.  The driver reported to OnStar that the cause of the crash was his inadvertent contact with the steering wheel that occurred when he bent down to pick something up off the floor of the vehicle.  This is consistent with telematics data, which indicates that the driver provided a manual override input into the steering wheel approximately four seconds before the crash.  This steering wheel input simultaneously disengaged Super Cruise and caused the sequence of events that led to the vehicle crashing into a fixed on-road barrier.  Super Cruise was not active at the time of the crash.  After the Crash, OnStar Emergency contacted the driver and found out the driver was alert and responsive, and requested emergency assistance.  GM believes, but has not confirmed, that the vehicle was towed from the scene.  Telematics data indicates that the driver was not belted at the time of the crash.   GM does not know whether the driver or any vehicle passengers were injured during the crash.

Narrative: According to the police report, at the time of the incident a 2016MY Chevrolet Impala was stationary northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane facing northwest.  The 2021MY Kia K5 was traveling northbound on [XXX], in the inside lane approaching the Chevrolet Impala. A 2008MY Honda Civic was traveling northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane behind the Kia K5.  Subsequently, the Kia K5's front struck the Chevrolet Impala's drivers side rear door and rear quarter panel.  After impact, the Impala traveled in a northwesterly, counterclockwise direction into a concrete barrier wall and bounced off the barrier wall and redirected to a northeasterly counterclockwise direction across the northbound lanes when the Honda Civic's front collided into the Chevrolet Impala's and left rear door.  The Chevrolet Impala came to rest facing north, blocking the inside lane. After impact, the Kia K5 traveled in a northeasterly direction across the northbound lanes and came to a final rest on the outside grass shoulder facing west.  The Honda Civic came to final rest blocking the outside lane adjacent to the Chevrolet Impala.  The subject Kia K5 is equipped with Highway Driving Assist (HDA).  HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance and speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway and helps keep the vehicle between lanes while driving.  HDA may not be able to recognize all traffic situations and may not detect possible collisions due to limitations of the system.  Obstacles such as vehicles, motorcycles, bicycles, pedestrians, unspecified objects and structures that may collide with the vehicle may not be detected. The owner (father of the driver) of the Kia K5 contacted Kia's Consumer Affairs Department on August [XXX], 2021 indicating that his son was involved in an accident.  The father was not a passenger or witness to the accident.  The father reported that HDA was engaged at the time of the incident and stated that his son "had the autopilot on and there was a vehicle in the middle of the road and it [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] did not notify his son."  According to the father, the police removed the "black box" from the vehicle.  The claims made by the driver's father have not yet been confirmed, and we note that the subject vehicle has no "autopilot" nor does Kia America advertise any ADAS feature as "autopilot."  Kia has no further information at this time.**9/[XXX]/2021 - No incremental information available as of 9/[XXX]/2021 2:26PM (PDT)
